did.unittitle: UNESCO Second Canadian Archaeological Expedition to Carthage Records

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This collection is organized into six series: Records and Reports from the Carthage digs; Field journals; Fiche reports; Excavation site images; Carthage site maps; and Carthage site drawings.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Colin Michael Wells was born on November 15, 1933 in West Bridgford, Notts, England. He attended Oriel College, Oxford from 1952 to 1954 before joining the Royal Artillery stationed in Egypt and Germany. Following his military service, he received his BA in 1958 from Oriel College, Oxford. In 1960, Wells accepted a position teaching at the University of Ottawa. He earned his doctorate in 1965 under the tutelage of Professor Ian Richmond.

Beginning in 1976, Wells led a team of researchers in excavations at Carthage. The initial excavations were part of an UNESCO campaign entitled "Save Carthage." The excavations focused on the Theodosian Wall and continued through 1986. In 1987, Wells went to Trinity University as the first Murchison Distinguished Professor of Classical Studies. In this role, he continued excavations at Carthage using the Odeon Hill site as an educational opportunity for Trinity students through 2002.

In addition to his archaeological work, Wells was a scholar of Roman frontiers and military under Augustus. He wrote and edited four books and over 120 articles examining the Roman frontier and army, Roman Africa, and changes in the empire under Augustan military activity.

Wells retired from Trinity University in 2004 after serving as chair of the classical studies department and as a member of several university committees. He was given the title of professor emeritus.
Wells married Kate Hughes in 1960. They had two sons, Christopher and Dominic. Wells passed away on March 11, 2010 at Banger in North Wales.

custodhist.head: Custodial History
custodhist.p: This collection was donated to DCA in February 2014 by Kate Wells, widow of C.M. (Colin Michael) Wells. From 1976 to 1986 C.M. Wells was director of the UNESCO Second Canadian Archaeological Expedition to Carthage in modern Tunisia. C.M. Wells died in March 2010 before completing a final report on the excavations, and the Wells family asked R. Bruce Hitchner, Professor of Classics and International Relations at Tufts, to continue the project. At Hitchner's request, the collection was transferred from Kate Wells to DCA to enable his research.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: This collection was processed by Erin Faulder, Archivist for Digital Collections, and Kendra Ciccone, Processing archivist in 2014.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection contains archaeological records, reports, field journals, small find reports, excavation site images, maps, tracings of mosaics and drawings from the UNESCO Second Canadian Archaeological Expedition to Carthage, led by Colin Wells. The records primarily cover the dig on section 2CC on the Northern Sector Theodosian Wall from of 1976 and 1986.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Some material in this collection may be protected by copyright and other rights. Please see "Reproductions and Use" on the Digital Collections and Archives website for more information about reproductions and permission to publish. Any intellectual property rights that the donor possesses have been transferred to Tufts University.

did.unittitle: Records and Reports from the Carthage digs

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains records from 1965-1999, from UNESCO's Second Canadian Archaeological dig led by Colin Wells at the 2CC Northern Sector of the Theodosian wall. The records primarily include Colin Wells's publications, reports, articles, and correspondence detailing the dig's efforts at the sites. Interspersed among the records are also plans, drawings, and black and white prints that may have corresponding material in other series.

This series also contains records from the archaeological dig sponsored by Trinity University and led by Colin Wells at the Hill of Odeon. These records include dig notes, records, and trench information.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged chronologically by date.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains field journals from 1976-1998 from UNESCO's Second Canadian Archaeological dig at the 2CC Northern Sector of the Theodosian wall and at the archaeological dig sponsored by Trinity University at the Hill of Odeon. The field journals are bound volumes where members of the archaeological team detailed the daily dig efforts, described small finds, and drew on-site maps. Authors of the journals include Colin Wells, Marianne Goodfellow, and Gerald Pelletier.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged chronologically by date.

did.unittitle: McIntosh and Ben Mhd. Amar 1982 & 1983 II

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains fiche reports from 1976-1998, pertaining to sections of UNESCO's Second Canadian Archaeological dig at the 2CC Northern Sector of the Theodosian wall, and small finds (menues trouvailles) and fiches from the archaeological dig sponsored by Trinity University at the Hill of Odeon. There are a few indices to the small finds sheets, particularly for the earlier years. Included at the end are reports and fiche specifically for material finds such as bone, shell, glass, stone, mosaics, and metal.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged by fiche type, then by location, and then chronologically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs, slides and images taken of the excavation sites from 1976-2002 at both the UNESCO's Second Canadian Archaeological dig at the 2CC Northern Sector of the Theodosian wall and at the archaeological dig sponsored by Trinity University at the Hill of Odeon. It also contains materials used for exhibits of the UNESCO Second Canadian Archaeological Expedition to Carthage. At the end of the series are images of other archaeological sites unrelated to the digs led by Colin Wells.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged by location and then roughly chronologically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains maps detailing the UNESCO's Second Canadian Archaeological dig at the 2CC Northern Sector of the Theodosian wall and the archaeological dig sponsored by Trinity University at the Hill of Odeon. There are published versions of the archaeological maps and hand-drawn stratigraphic maps.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged in two sub-series.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This sub-series contains printed and published maps from between 1913 and 1998, UNESCO's Second Canadian Archaeological dig at the 2CC Northern Sector of the Theodosian wall and the archaeological dig sponsored by Trinity University at the Hill of Odeon. The maps show the evolution of the dig locations as trenches were further uncovered and evaluated. There are also maps of Carthage and Tunisia.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged chronologically by date.
